@node "Reason" "The motive behind Sample-X"
@{fg shine}TG300@{fg text} is the ultimate Yamaha TG300 patch editor for the Amiga. It allows you
to edit most of the sound parameters from the computer. Therefore, you no
longer have to be hunched over your synth, using that thumbwheel and four
cursor keys.

Again, this product is a result of becoming fed up with using the front panel
of my TG300 to tweak sounds. This tone module has loads of sound creation
potential but the interface is too restricting. With this new patch editor
there are no such restrictions. All the parameters can be easily adjusted on
the computer screen.

I did think about doing a universal patch editor, but then I may never have
finished the software... universal editors have to be incredibly well
designed. I don't particularly want to concentrate on coding patch editors. I
want to make music.

Bye
        Sheun Olatunbosun 15-5-98
@endnode

@node "Register" "Register"
Okay, there's nothing for you here. The program is absolutely free. Once
again, send @{"me" link "Author" 0} some email. I'm just interested in getting some feedback from
you Amiga musicians out there.

In particular, I'm interested in coding a patch editor for the Yamaha XG
range. If anybody can provide the necessary SysEx information, I might just
code it.
@endnode

@node "SystemReq" "System requirements"
@{fg shine}TG300@{fg text} requires @{b}Workbench 2.04+@{ub} and of course a@{b}Yamaha TG300@{ub} tone module. It
won't be much use otherwise, unless you want to look at the gorgeous interface
:-).

The @{b}midi.library@{ub} is also required.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
@{b}TG300@{ub} has the following features


   - System, Part, Voice, Drum, Effect editing
   - Suspend operation
   - MIDI monitor window
   - Intuitive GUI layout
   - Retargettable MIDI ports
@endnode

@node "GetStart" "Getting Started"
Run the installation script which simply copies the "newtopaz" font to your
FONTS directory (this font is so much nicer than the default Workbench one).

You can start@{b} TG300@{ub} from the CLI by entering 'TG300' or double clicking on its
icon from Workbench. TG300 will then attempt to open on its own screen.

@{i}If TG300 fails to start then make sure that you have the midi.library
installed in the LIBS: directory and the newtopaz font in the FONTS:@{ui}

Connect the MIDI OUT port of an external keyboard to the MIDI IN port of the
MIDI interface of the Amiga. Then connect the MIDI OUT of this interface to
the MIDI IN port of the TG300.

That's it! Start tweaking and listen to the changes.

Right, all that remains is to explain the meaning of the various features of
@{"TG300" link "TG300Screen" 0}.
@endnode

